\hypertarget{skydynamics-robotics-control-engineer-technical-challenge}{%
\section{SkyDynamics Robotics --- Control Engineer Technical Challenge}\label{skydynamics-robotics-control-engineer-technical-challenge}}

Implement PID, LQR, and MPC Controllers from Sensor Bag Data

Position: Control Engineer • Team: Flight Control Systems\\
Pre-Interview Technical Assessment • Estimated Time: 3 Hours

\hypertarget{company-brief-skydynamics-robotics}{%
\subsection{Company Brief: SkyDynamics Robotics}\label{company-brief-skydynamics-robotics}}

\textbf{Scenario:} SkyDynamics Robotics is developing a next-generation autonomous ground robot platform for warehouse logistics. Your team has collected 30 seconds of sensor data (odometry, IMU, and reference trajectory) from a prototype run. As part of this technical challenge, you will implement three control strategies as ROS2 nodes and compare their performance on the recorded data.

\hypertarget{provided-bag-data}{%
\subsubsection{Provided Bag Data}\label{provided-bag-data}}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Topic & Message Type & Rate & Description \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\texttt{/odom} & nav\_msgs/Odometry & 50 Hz & Robot odometry (position, orientation, velocity) \\
\texttt{/imu} & sensor\_msgs/Imu & 200 Hz & Inertial measurement unit data \\
\texttt{/reference\_trajectory} & geometry\_msgs/PoseStamped & 50 Hz & Desired waypoint trajectory \\
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{deliverables}{%
\subsubsection{Deliverables}\label{deliverables}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  A PID controller ROS2 node with anti-windup and runtime-tunable gains
\item
  An LQR controller ROS2 node using scipy Riccati solver with state-space model
\item
  An MPC controller ROS2 node with horizon-based trajectory optimisation
\item
  A launch file that replays bag data and runs all three controllers simultaneously
\item
  A quantitative comparison: rise time, overshoot, steady-state error, and computation time
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{evaluation-criteria}{%
\subsubsection{Evaluation Criteria}\label{evaluation-criteria}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Code Quality:} Clean ROS2 node structure, proper QoS configuration, parameter declarations
\item
  \textbf{Control Theory:} Correct discrete-time implementation, stability analysis, gain tuning rationale
\item
  \textbf{Systems Thinking:} Modular architecture, proper topic naming, error handling
\item
  \textbf{Communication:} Ability to explain design decisions and trade-offs during the follow-up interview
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{skills-you-will-demonstrate}{%
\subsection{Skills You Will Demonstrate}\label{skills-you-will-demonstrate}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Explain the architecture of a ROS2 control node, including publishers, subscribers, timers, and parameter servers, and describe how they map to classical control-loop components.
\item
  Implement PID, LQR, and MPC controllers as standalone ROS2 Python nodes that subscribe to odometry and publish velocity commands.
\item
  Describe the \texttt{ros2\_control} framework and its layered architecture: hardware interface, controller manager, and controller plugins.
\item
  Configure Quality of Service (QoS) policies for control topics, choosing appropriate reliability and deadline settings for real-time performance.
\item
  Compare and contrast MATLAB/Simulink and ROS2 implementations of the same control algorithm, identifying trade-offs in prototyping speed, real-time guarantees, and deployment readiness.
\item
  Use ROS2 parameters and launch files to switch between controller types and tune gains at runtime without recompilation.
\item
  Record, replay, and analyse control performance data using \texttt{rosbag2}, extracting metrics such as rise time, overshoot, and steady-state error.
\item
  Design a modular ROS2 control architecture that separates state estimation, controller logic, and actuation into distinct nodes communicating over well-defined topics.
\end{itemize}

