\hypertarget{expected-rviz2-output}{%
\subsubsection{Expected RViz2 Output}\label{expected-rviz2-output}}

RViz2 will display the robot\textquotesingle s odometry path (white), the reference trajectory (green), and the controller command markers. You should see the robot following the reference trajectory with the three controllers producing slightly different tracking behaviour.

\hypertarget{troubleshooting}{%
\subsubsection{Troubleshooting}\label{troubleshooting}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{RViz2 crashes on launch:} The launch file filters \texttt{snap} paths from \texttt{LD\_LIBRARY\_PATH} automatically. If RViz2 still crashes, try: \texttt{export\ LD\_LIBRARY\_PATH=\$(echo\ \$LD\_LIBRARY\_PATH\ \textbar{}\ tr\ \textquotesingle{}:\textquotesingle{}\ \textquotesingle{}\textbackslash{}n\textquotesingle{}\ \textbar{}\ grep\ -v\ snap\ \textbar{}\ tr\ \textquotesingle{}\textbackslash{}n\textquotesingle{}\ \textquotesingle{}:\textquotesingle{})}
\item
  \textbf{No data visible:} Ensure the bag file exists at \texttt{w11\_exercises/bag\_data/synthetic\_control/}. Re-run \texttt{colcon\ build} if needed.
\item
  \textbf{QoS mismatch warnings:} The bag uses default QoS. If your subscriber uses \texttt{BEST\_EFFORT}, switch to \texttt{RELIABLE} or use \texttt{-\/-qos-profile-overrides-path}.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{appendix-review-material-lqrlqg-optimal-control}{%
\subsection{Appendix: Review Material --- LQR/LQG Optimal Control}\label{appendix-review-material-lqrlqg-optimal-control}}

\hypertarget{question-1-derivation-of-the-continuous-algebraic-riccati-equation-25-marks}{%
\paragraph{Question 1 --- Derivation of the Continuous Algebraic Riccati Equation (25 marks)}\label{question-1-derivation-of-the-continuous-algebraic-riccati-equation-25-marks}}

Consider a linear time-invariant system:

\[
                    \dot{x} = Ax + Bu, \qquad x(0) = x_0
                \]

with the infinite-horizon quadratic cost:

\[
                    J = \int_0^{\infty} \bigl(x^T Q\,x + u^T R\,u\bigr)\,dt
                \]

where \(Q \succeq 0\) and \(R \succ 0\).

\textbf{(a)} Starting from the Hamilton--Jacobi--Bellman (HJB) equation with value function \(V(x) = x^T P\,x\), derive the continuous algebraic Riccati equation (CARE). Show every step of the derivation. (15 marks)

\textbf{(b)} Explain how the weighting matrices \(Q\) and \(R\) affect the closed-loop pole locations. In particular, describe what happens as \(R \to 0\) and as \(Q \to 0\). (10 marks)

\hypertarget{model-answer-a-care-derivation}{%
\paragraph{Model Answer (a) --- CARE Derivation}\label{model-answer-a-care-derivation}}

\textbf{Step 1:} Assume the optimal value function takes the quadratic form \(V^*(x) = x^T P\,x\) where \(P = P^T \succ 0\). The HJB equation for the infinite-horizon problem is:

\[
                        0 = \min_{u}\Bigl\{x^T Q\,x + u^T R\,u + \frac{\partial V^*}{\partial x}^T(Ax + Bu)\Bigr\}
                    \]

\textbf{Step 2:} Compute the gradient: \(\frac{\partial V^*}{\partial x} = 2Px\). Substituting:

\[
                        0 = \min_{u}\bigl\{x^T Q\,x + u^T R\,u + 2x^T P(Ax + Bu)\bigr\}
                    \]

\textbf{Step 3:} Minimise with respect to \(u\). Taking the derivative and setting to zero:

\[
                        \frac{\partial}{\partial u}\bigl[u^T R\,u + 2x^T P B\,u\bigr] = 2R\,u + 2B^T P\,x = 0
                    \]
\[
                        \implies u^* = -R^{-1}B^T P\,x
                    \]

\textbf{Step 4:} Substitute \(u^*\) back into the HJB equation:

\[
                        0 = x^T Q\,x + x^T P B R^{-1} R\, R^{-1} B^T P\,x - 2x^T P B R^{-1} B^T P\,x + 2x^T P A\,x
                    \]
\[
                        0 = x^T\!\bigl[Q + PA + A^T P - PBR^{-1}B^T P\bigr]x
                    \]

\textbf{Step 5:} Since this must hold for all \(x\), we obtain the \textbf{CARE}:

\[
                        \boxed{A^T P + PA - PBR^{-1}B^T P + Q = 0}
                    \]

The optimal state-feedback gain is \(K = R^{-1}B^T P\), yielding \(u^* = -Kx\).

\hypertarget{model-answer-b-effect-of-q-and-r-on-closed-loop-poles}{%
\paragraph{Model Answer (b) --- Effect of Q and R on Closed-Loop Poles}\label{model-answer-b-effect-of-q-and-r-on-closed-loop-poles}}

The closed-loop system is \(\dot{x} = (A - BK)x\), where \(K = R^{-1}B^T P\). The poles are the eigenvalues of \(A_{cl} = A - BK\).

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{As \(R \to 0\):} The control cost vanishes, so the controller uses arbitrarily large inputs. The gain \(K\) grows without bound, and the closed-loop poles move far into the left-half plane (very fast response). In the limit, the LQR poles approach the transmission zeros of the system or recede to infinity along Butterworth patterns.
\item
  \textbf{As \(Q \to 0\):} The state penalty vanishes, so there is no incentive to drive the state to zero. The gain \(K \to 0\), and the closed-loop poles approach the open-loop poles of the plant. The system behaves almost as if there is no feedback.
\item
  \textbf{Increasing \(Q/R\) ratio:} Moves poles further into the LHP (faster, more aggressive control, higher bandwidth). Decreasing \(Q/R\) moves poles closer to the imaginary axis (slower, more conservative, less control effort).
\end{itemize}

A key property of LQR is that all closed-loop poles are guaranteed to lie in the open left-half plane (stability) and the system has at least 60° phase margin and infinite gain margin (robustness).

\hypertarget{question-2-the-separation-principle-in-lqg-25-marks}{%
\paragraph{Question 2 --- The Separation Principle in LQG (25 marks)}\label{question-2-the-separation-principle-in-lqg-25-marks}}

Consider a stochastic LTI system with process noise \(w\) and measurement noise \(v\):

\[
                    \dot{x} = Ax + Bu + w, \qquad y = Cx + v
                \]

where \(w \sim \mathcal{N}(0, W)\) and \(v \sim \mathcal{N}(0, V)\).

\textbf{(a)} State the \emph{separation principle} (also called the \emph{certainty-equivalence principle}) for LQG control. Explain why it allows the state estimator (Kalman filter) and the state-feedback controller (LQR) to be designed independently. (15 marks)

\textbf{(b)} Discuss scenarios where you would use LQG instead of LQR. What are the practical limitations of LQG? (10 marks)

\hypertarget{model-answer-a-the-separation-principle}{%
\paragraph{Model Answer (a) --- The Separation Principle}\label{model-answer-a-the-separation-principle}}

\textbf{Statement:} For a linear system with Gaussian noise and a quadratic cost, the optimal controller consists of two independent components:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Kalman filter (state estimator):} Computes the optimal state estimate \(\hat{x}\) using the system model and noisy measurements:
  \[
                              \dot{\hat{x}} = A\hat{x} + Bu + L(y - C\hat{x}), \qquad L = \Sigma C^T V^{-1}
                          \]
  where \(\Sigma\) solves the \emph{filter} algebraic Riccati equation: \(A\Sigma + \Sigma A^T - \Sigma C^T V^{-1} C\Sigma + W = 0\).
\item
  \textbf{LQR gain:} Computes the optimal feedback \(u = -K\hat{x}\), where \(K = R^{-1}B^T P\) and \(P\) solves the standard CARE.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Why independent design works:} The estimation error \(\tilde{x} = x - \hat{x}\) evolves as \(\dot{\tilde{x}} = (A - LC)\tilde{x} + w - Lv\), which is independent of the control input \(u\). The closed-loop eigenvalues are the union of the LQR poles (eigenvalues of \(A - BK\)) and the Kalman filter poles (eigenvalues of \(A - LC\)). Since these sets are decoupled, each component can be designed without knowledge of the other.

\hypertarget{model-answer-b-when-to-use-lqg-over-lqr}{%
\paragraph{Model Answer (b) --- When to Use LQG over LQR}\label{model-answer-b-when-to-use-lqg-over-lqr}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Noisy measurements:} When sensor data is corrupted by significant noise (e.g., IMU drift, lidar noise), LQR alone would amplify noise through the feedback gain. The Kalman filter in LQG provides optimal noise filtering.
\item
  \textbf{Incomplete state measurement:} When not all states are directly measurable (e.g., velocity must be estimated from position), the Kalman filter reconstructs unmeasured states.
\item
  \textbf{Process disturbances:} When the system is subject to stochastic disturbances (wind gusts, ground vibration), LQG accounts for these statistically through the process noise covariance \(W\).
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Practical limitations of LQG:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{No guaranteed robustness margins:} Unlike LQR, LQG does \emph{not} have guaranteed gain/phase margins. The Loop Transfer Recovery (LTR) technique can partially restore robustness.
\item
  \textbf{Model accuracy:} Performance degrades significantly if the system model or noise covariances \(W, V\) are inaccurate.
\item
  \textbf{Linearity assumption:} LQG is optimal only for linear systems with Gaussian noise. For nonlinear systems, Extended Kalman Filters (EKF) or Unscented Kalman Filters (UKF) are needed, but optimality guarantees are lost.
\item
  \textbf{Computational cost:} Requires solving two Riccati equations and running the Kalman filter in real time, though this is typically manageable for modern hardware.
\end{itemize}

